[
    {
        "content": "<p>I need the following fact.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Let <code>E</code> and <code>F</code> be finite dimensional real normed spaces.<br>\nLet <code>μ</code> and <code>ν</code> be additive Haar measures on these spaces.<br>\nLet <code>s : Set (E × F)</code> be a measurable set (in the original informal text, <code>s</code> is a closed set).<br>\nThen for <code>(μ.prod ν)</code>-ae <code>(x, y) ∈ s</code>, <code>x</code> is a μ-density point of <code>{z | (z, y) ∈ s}</code>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The original informal text deduces by applying Lebesgue density theorem to each <code>{z | (z, y) ∈ s}</code>. AFAICT, we also need to show that the set <code>{(x, y) | x is a μ-density pt of {z | (z, y) ∈ s}}</code> is a measurable set. What are the right assumptions for this statement?</p>",
        "id": 488778859,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1734074016
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Clearly, \"finite dimensional normed spaces + Haar measures\" is too strong.</p>",
        "id": 488778904,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1734074039
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that I can drop all assumptions on <code>F</code> (possibly, except for <code>ν</code> being an s-finite measure). Does it make sense to weaken assumptions on <code>E</code>?</p>",
        "id": 488780129,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1734074636
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I can show that the ratio of the measures is a measurable function, thus the set of points where it tends to 1 along positive rational numbers is a measurable set (w/o assuming that <code>μ</code> is a Haar measure), but I need some assumptions to switch to the limit along positive real numbers.</p>",
        "id": 488780373,
        "sender_full_name": "Yury G. Kudryashov",
        "timestamp": 1734074760
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Isn't the set of density points the set of points where the ratio <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>∩</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu(s \\cap B(x, r)) / \\mu(B(x, r))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∩</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> tends to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> along rational <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span></span></span></span>, and the same for closed balls? If so, everyting is expressed countably, so everything is measurable.</p>",
        "id": 488788682,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1734078441
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thinking back about this, there is even no need to take both open and closed balls. If you define density points using open balls, you can use that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu(B(x,t))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> is the limit as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span></span></span></span> tends to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> from below of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu(B(x, r))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> to deduce that convergence along the rationals implies convergence along the reals. And if you use closed balls, note that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">‾</mo></mover><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu(\\overline{B}(x,t))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1333em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord overline\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8833em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.8033em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"overline-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> is the limit as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span></span></span></span> tends to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> from above of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">‾</mo></mover><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu(\\overline{B}(x, r))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1333em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord overline\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8833em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.8033em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"overline-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> to conclude in the same way.</p>",
        "id": 488809938,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1734085817
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This only works at points where the measure is locally finite, but if the measure is not locally finite then we don't have a density point as the ratio <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>∩</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>μ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu(s \\cap B(x, r)) / \\mu(B(x,r))</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∩</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span></span></span></span> is always zero, so convergence along the rationals iff along the reals is also true.</p>",
        "id": 488810310,
        "sender_full_name": "Sébastien Gouëzel",
        "timestamp": 1734085949
    },
    {
